ategory:Hong Kong martial arts films]]\n[[Category:Police Story (film series) films]]\n[[Category:Action films by series]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Hong Kong action film series}}\n{{other uses|Police Story (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Police Story <br />\u8b66\u5bdf\u6545\u4e8b\u7cfb\u5217\n| image          = Policestoryseries.jpg\n| caption        = Hong Kong Blu-ray box set for the first three ''Police Story'' films\n| film name = {{Film name| traditional    = \u8b66\u5bdf\u6545\u4e8b\u7cfb\u5217\n| simplified     = \u8b66\u5bdf\u6545\u4e8b\u7cfb\u5217\n| pinyin         = J\u01d0ngch\u00e1 G\u00f9sh\u00ec X\u00ec Li\u00e8\n| jyutping       = Ging2 Caat3 Gu3 Si6 Hai6 Lit6}}\n| director       = [[Jackie Chan]] ([[Police Story (1985 film)|I]], [[Police Story 2|II]])<br />[[Stanley Tong]] ([[Police Story III: Super Cop|III]], [[Police Story IV: First Strike (film)|IV]], [[Once a Cop]])<br />[[Benny Chan (film director)|Benny Chan]] ([[New Police Story|V]])<br />[[Ding Sheng (director)|Ding Sheng]] ([[Police Story 2013|VI]])\n| producer       = [[Raymond Chow]] (I, II)<br />[[Leonard Ho]] (I-III)<br />Jackie Chan (III)<br />Barbie Tung (IV, V, Once a Cop)<br />Willie Chan (III, V)<br />Solon So (V)<br />Yang Du (VI)\n| writer         = Jackie Chan (I, II)<br />Edward Tang (I-III)<br />Ma Fibe<br />Yee Lee-Wai (III)<br />Stanley Tong (IV, Once a Cop)<br />Elliot Tong<br />Greg Mellott<br />Nick Tramontane (IV)<br />Alan Yuen (V)<br />Ding Sheng (VI)<br />Sandy Shaw (Once a Cop)\n| starring       = [[Jackie Chan]] <br />[[Bill Tung]] <br />[[Brigitte Lin]] <br />[[Maggie Cheung]]<br />[[Lam Kwok-Hung]] <br />[[Chor Yuen]]<br />[[Charlie Cho]]<br />[[Mars (actor)|Mars]]<br />[[Michelle Yeoh]]<br />[[Yuen Wah]]<br />[[Annie Wu (actress)|Annie Wu]]<br />[[:zh:\u6a13\u5b78\u8ce2|Jackson Liu]]<br />[[Nicholas Tse]]<br />[[Charlie Young (actress)|Charlie Yeung]]<br />[[Charlene Choi]]<br />[[Daniel Wu]]<br />[[Yu Rongguang]]<br />[[Jing Tian]]<br />[[Liu Ye (actor)|Liu Ye]]\n| music          = Michael Lai<br />Kevin Bassinson (I, export version) <ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T7jwCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA248&lpg=PA248&dq=%22kevin+bassinson%22+%22police+story%22&source=bl&ots=ZDzCFWhf9i&sig=ACfU3U3DTKHCVNX-WGGfqkcuVO-E922EPg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwif6M6m1ozoAhWKbc0KHc67C5Y4ChDoATAGegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=%22kevin%20bassinson%22%20%22police%20story%22&f=false|work=John Charles|title=The Hong Kong Filmography, 1977-1997: A Reference Guide to 1,100 Films Produced by British Hong Kong Studios|date=25 June 2015}}</ref> <br />Tang Siu-Lam (I, II)<br />Mac Chew<br />Jenny Chinn<br />[[Jonathan Lee (record producer)|Jonathan Lee]] (III)<br />[[Nathan Wang]] (IV)<br />Tommy Wai (V)<br />Zai Lao (VI)<br />Richard Lo (Once a Cop)\n| cinematography = Cheung Yiu-Cho (I, II)<br />Danny Lee Yau Tong (II)<br />Ardy Lam (III, Once a Cop)<br />[[Jingle Ma]] (IV)<br />Anthony Pun (V)<br />Yu Ding (VI)\n| editing        = Peter Cheung (I-IV, Once a Cop)<br />[[Cheung Ka-fai (film editor)|Cheung Ka-Fai]] (III, Once a Cop)<br />Yau Chi-Wai (IV, V)<br />Ding Sheng (VI)\n| distributor    = '''Hong Kong:'''<br />[[Orange Sky Golden Harvest|Golden Harvest]]<br />[[Media Asia Entertainment Group|Media Asia]]<br />Golden Way Films Co. Ltd.<br />[[JCE Movies Limited]]<br />[[Emperor Motion Pictures]]<br />[[China Film Group Corporation]]<br />Fortune Star Media Ltd.\n| released       = [[Hong Kong films of 1985|1985]], [[Hong Kong films of 1988|1988]], [[Hong Kong films of 1992|1992]], [[Hong Kong films of 1993|1993]], [[Hong Kong films of 1996|1996]], [[Hong Kong films of 2004|2004]], [[List of Hong Kong films of 2013|2013]]\n| country        = Hong Kong\n| language       = '''Cantonese:'''<br />(I, II, III, IV, V, Once a Cop)<br />'''Mandarin:'''<br />(VI)<br />'''English:'''<br />(III, IV)\n| runtime        = 743 minutes (combined)\n| budget         =\n| gross          = [[HK$]]254,795,969 {{small|(Hong{{nbsp}}Kong)}}<br />{{US$|264.25 million|link=yes}} {{small|(worldwide)}}\n}}\n'''''Police Story''''' ({{zh|\u8b66\u5bdf\u6545\u4e8b\u7cfb\u5217}}) comprises [[List of film series with six entries|six]] official [[Cinema of Hong Kong|Hong Kong]] [[crime film|crime]]-[[Hong Kong action cinema|action films]], starring [[Jackie Chan]], directed by Jackie Chan, [[Stanley Tong]], [[Benny Chan (film director)|Benny Chan]], and [[Ding Sheng (director)|Ding Sheng]], and produced by [[Raymond Chow]], [[Leonard Ho]], Jackie Chan, Barbie Tung, [[Willie Chan]], Solon So and Yang Du. The first film ''[[Police Story (1985 film)|Police Story]]'' was released on 14 December 1985. The film's success led to five sequels and one spin-off.\n\n[[Jackie Chan|Chan]] began work on the film after a disappointing experience working with director [[James Glickenhaus]] on ''[[The Protector (1985 film)|The Protector]]'', which was intended to be his entry into the [[Cinema of United States|American film]] market. The first ''Police Story'' film is considered by fans to be one of Chan's best films. It was a massive hit in Asia. According to his autobiography, ''[[I Am Jackie Chan]]'', Chan considers the film his best, in terms of action and [[stunt]]s. The first three ''Police Story'' films were voted among the [[List of films considered the best|best action films]] of all time in ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]''{{'}}s poll of film critics, directors, actors, and stunt actors, with ''Police Story'' ranked 4th,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/newyork/film/best-action-movies|work=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]|title=The 100 best action movies|date=29 April 2016}}</ref> ''[[Police Story II]]'' ranked 61st,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/newyork/film/the-100-best-action-movies-70-61|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141116140621/http://www.timeout.com/newyork/film/the-100-best-action-movies-70-61|url-status=dead|archive-date=16 November 2014|work=Time Out|access-date=7 November 2014|date=3 November 2014|title=The 100 best action movies: 70\u201361}}</ref> and ''[[Police Story III: Super Cop]]'' ranked 75th.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/newyork/film/the-100-best-action-movies-80-71|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141116140621/http://www.timeout.com/newyork/film/the-100-best-action-movies-80-71|url-status=dead|archive-date=16 November 2014|work=Time Out|access-date=7 November 2014|title=The 100 best action movies: 80\u201371}}</ref>\n\n==Films==\nAll of the ''Police Story'' films were [[Film producer|produced]] by [[Raymond Chow]], [[Leonard Ho]], Jackie Chan, Barbie Tung, Willie Chan, Solon So and Yang Du, distributed by [[Orange Sky Golden Harvest|Golden Harvest]], [[Media Asia Entertainment Group|Media Asia]], Golden Way Films Co. Ltd., Fortune Star Media Ltd., and [[JCE Movies Limited|JCE Movies]]. They were all directed by Jackie Chan, [[Stanley Tong]], [[Benny Chan (film director)|Benny Chan]] and [[Ding Sheng (director)|Ding Sheng]].\n\n===''Police Story'' (1985)===\n{{Main|Police Story (1985 film)}}\n\n''Police Story'' ({{zh|t=\u8b66\u5bdf\u6545\u4e8b}}) was released in [[Hong Kong films of 1985|1985]]. The [[Royal Hong Kong Police Force]] is planning a major undercover sting called \"Operation Boar Hunt\" to arrest crime lord Chu Tao ([[Chor Yuen]]). Inspector Chan Ka-Kui (or Kevin Chan in some versions) is part of the operation, along with undercover officers stationed in a shanty town. After arresting Chu, Chan's next assignment is to protect Chu Tao's secretary, Selina Fong ([[Brigitte Lin]]), who plans to testify in court about Chu Tao's illegal activities. The trial fails due to Selina's tampering with evidence. Chu Tao is released on bail and plots revenge against Ka-Kui, framing him for the murder of fellow policeman Inspector Man. Meanwhile, Selina, realizing Chu's criminality, goes to his office at a shopping mall to download incriminating data from Chu Tao's computer system. Chu Tao and Chan notice this and head to the mall. In the ensuing fight, Ka-Kui defeats all of Chu Tao's henchmen while the police apprehend Chu and the briefcase.\n\n===''Police Story II'' (1988)===\n{{Main|Police Story II}}\n''Police Story II'' ({{zh|t=\u8b66\u5bdf\u6545\u4e8b\u7e8c\u96c6}} or ''Police Story Part II''), released in [[Hong Kong films of 1988|1988]], featured many of the same actors reprising their roles from the original. The story picks up with Chan Ka-Kui being demoted to a traffic cop for causing so much damage in his apprehension of Chu. Chu has been released from prison on the pretense that he is terminally ill, and Chu and his clan continue to harass Chan and his girlfriend May as Chan gets reinstated to the detective unit when criminal bombers begin extorting money from businessmen. The film marks the last appearance of [[Lam Kwok-Hung]] as Superintendent Raymond Li.\n\n===''Police Story III: Super Cop'' (1992)===\n{{Main|Police Story III: Super Cop}}\n''Police Story III: Super Cop'' ({{zh|t=\u8b66\u5bdf\u6545\u4e8b3\u8d85\u7d1a\u8b66\u5bdf}} or ''Supercop'') was released in [[Hong Kong films of 1992|1992]]. [[Michelle Yeoh]] joins the cast, portraying a police officer from mainland China. The story involves Chan and Yeoh's character going undercover to try to break up a drug smuggling ring. The action moves from China to [[Kuala Lumpur]], where Chan's girlfriend May is kidnapped. The film marks the last appearance of [[Maggie Cheung]] as May. Michelle Yeoh reprises her role in the spin-off, called ''[[Once a Cop]]''. [[Dimension Films]] released the film in the US in 1996 under the title ''Supercop'', with some edits to the film, the complete replacement of all music and sound effects, and English [[Dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbing]].\n\n===''Once a Cop'' (1993)===\n{{Main|Once a Cop}}\n''Once a Cop'' ({{zh|t=\u8d85\u7d1a\u8a08\u5283}}, also known as ''Project S'' or ''Supercop 2''), released in [[Hong Kong films of 1993|1993]], is a Hong Kong [[Hong Kong action cinema|action film]] directed by [[Stanley Tong]] and starring [[Michelle Yeoh]]. It is a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] of [[Jackie Chan]]'s ''Police Story'' film series involving the character Yeoh portrayed in ''Police Story III: Super Cop'', Inspector Jessica Yang. The film is also known as ''Project S'' in original territories and many other titles, including ''Police Story IV'' (inaccurately), ''Police Story 3 Part 2'', and ''Supercop 2'' (US).\n\nBoth Jackie Chan and Bill Tung have cameo appearances as Inspector Chan Ka-Kui and \"Uncle\" Bill Wong in the film. Although Jackie Chan only has a [[cameo appearance]], some DVD covers prominently featured Chan, misleading audience to think that he was one of the main characters. He reprises his role as Inspector Chan, but in drag to catch a criminal in drag wearing the same wig and clothes.\n\n===''Police Story IV: First Strike'' (1996)===\n{{Main|Police Story IV: First Strike (film)}}\n''Police Story IV: First Strike'' ({{zh|t=\u8b66\u5bdf\u6545\u4e8b4\u4e4b\u7c21\u55ae\u4efb\u52d9}} also known as ''First Strike'' or ''Jackie Chan's First Strike'') was released in [[Hong Kong films of 1996|1996]] and is the only film in the ''Police Story'' series made partially in English. Jackie reprises his role as Chan Ka-Kui (also known in some versions as Jackie) for the final time as the Hong Kong cop works with Interpol to track down and arrest an illegal weapons dealer. Later Ka-Kui realizes that things are not as simple as they appear and soon finds himself a pawn of an organization posing as Russian intelligence. The action shifts away from Hong Kong and Asia, with a globe trekking [[espionage]] plot, lending the film the air of a [[James Bond]] adventure. The [[New Line Cinema]] release in the US contained various alterations. Filmed on location in [[Ukraine]] and [[Australia]], the film also marks the last appearance of [[Bill Tung]], who plays Chan's superior \"Uncle\" Bill Wong in the series.\n\n===''New Police Story'' (2004)===\n{{Main|New Police Story}}\n''New Police Story'' ({{zh|t=\u65b0\u8b66\u5bdf\u6545\u4e8b}}), released in [[Hong Kong films of 2004|2004]], is a [[Reboot (continuity)|reboot]] of the ''Police Story'' series. Chan portrays a disgraced detective named Chan Kwok-Wing, who accidentally leads his team into a trap from which he is the only survivor. Drowning his guilt in booze, he is eventually assigned a new younger partner who turns out to have his own secrets. However, they must work together if they are to stop the gang who killed Chan's team a year earlier. The film features younger Hong Kong actors such as [[Nicholas Tse]], [[Charlene Choi]], [[Charlie Young (actress)|Charlie Yeung]] and [[Daniel Wu]]. The story features a more dramatic focus, taking a darker and more serious tone.\n\n===''Police Story 2013'' (2013)===\n{{Main|Police Story 2013}}\n''Police Story 2013'' ({{zh|t=\u8b66\u5bdf\u6545\u4e8b2013}}), released in [[List of Hong Kong films of 2013|2013]], stars [[Jackie Chan]] in another reboot of the series. The film is directed by [[Ding Sheng (director)|Ding Sheng]], who previously helmed Chan's ''[[Little Big Soldier]]''. Unlike the previous Police Story films where he portrayed a Hong Kong cop, Jackie portrays a mainland Chinese officer named Zhong Wen. Zhong heads to Wu Bar in search of his estranged daughter, Miao Miao ([[Jing Tian]]). He disapproves of Miao's relationship with Wu Jiang ([[Liu Ye (actor)|Liu Ye]]), the nightclub owner. However, Wu, who is looking for the release of a long-time prisoner, takes Zhong, Miao, and a group of strangers hostage. The film was distributed as '''''Police Story: Lockdown''''' in the United States by Well Go USA Entertainment and released in June 2015.\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office performance===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\" style=\"width:99%; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Film\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Year\n! colspan=\"8\" | Gross revenue\n|-\n!